{"actual_usd":0.158605,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":358,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30647,"reply":"\"I'll tell you plain.\" *I shift my weight on the bench and glance across the bright square a moment, wanting to get the order right instead of making it prettier than it was.* \"A man with a camera would not have gotten a tidy triumphal sequence with music under it. He'd have gotten a dark graveyard before sunrise, women coming with spices, the stone already moved, confusion, fear, running feet, angels if the camera could bear that sight, and then—after that—the risen Jesus appearing to people in fits and starts.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of my Bible.* \"The actual first human-visible fact is not 'they saw Him step out' but 'the tomb was empty already.' That's important. Scripture never gives us a blow-by-blow of the instant of resurrection itself, like the lid popping off a box. What it gives us is the aftermath: the stone rolled away, messengers announcing He is risen, Mary weeping and then recognizing Him, disciples startled half to death, and over the days after that, repeated appearances to real people.\"\n\n\"If you'd had a camera aimed right at the tomb all night, I suspect you'd have seen soldiers on edge, the hour turning toward dawn, and at some terrible-beautiful moment a glory no machine was built to explain. But if we're sticking to what the Gospels actually say, the camera's clearest footage would be this: the grave was empty, and then Jesus was seen alive by witnesses who knew Him well enough not to mistake another man for their Lord.\"\n\n*I look back at you, steady.* \"If you want, I can do the next step carefully too—just the Gospel data, scene by scene, as if we're storyboarding the footage.\"","rolling_24h_usd":85.83357000000001,"run_id":"3ae1956d-55eb-4486-8d18-ce59c5656077"}
